	<h2>Why Traditional Call Handling Falls Short</h2>
	<p>Traditional human-operated call centers struggle with emergency scenarios due to several critical limitations:</p>

	<h3>Response Time Challenges</h3>
	<p>Human operators require time to assess situations, lookup protocols, and make decisions. During emergencies, every second counts. Studies show that <strong>72% of emergency calls require immediate action within the first 60 seconds</strong> - a timeframe that's challenging for human operators to consistently meet.</p>

	<h3>Availability Gaps</h3>
	<p>Most businesses operate during standard hours, leaving emergency calls unattended during nights, weekends, and holidays. This creates significant vulnerability periods when crises are most likely to escalate.</p>

	<h3>Consistency Issues</h3>
	<p>Human operators may handle similar emergencies differently based on experience, stress levels, or available information. This inconsistency can lead to suboptimal outcomes and potential liability issues.</p>

	<blockquote>
		"The average business loses $5,600 per hour during emergency situations due to delayed response times and inadequate call handling protocols." - Emergency Response Institute
	</blockquote>

